items.title: Russia suspected over blasts appearing to target Ukrainian police
items.author: Harry Fawcett
items.content:
Russia is thought to have been responsible for two bomb explosions which appear to have been set off to target Ukrainian police officers.

A 23-year-old police woman was killed and several people were injured by two improvised explosive devices in Lviv.

Russia also launched almost 300 drones and 50 missiles at Ukraine overnight.

items.title: How Fast is Japan’s Corporate Culture Changing?
items.author: Bloomberg Television
items.content:
<article>For decades, Japan’s corporate identity was seen by many to be characterized by lifetime employment, keiretsu networks, and cautious capital allocation. Now, inflation, market reform, and investor pressure are forcing change. Leaders at Sony, Panasonic Automotive, and the Tokyo Stock Exchange are rethinking the way they do business.. But as Mireya Solís and Apollo’s Eiji Ueda explain, transforming balance sheets may be easier than transforming culture.

items.title: Trump's new tariffs: What are Europe's options? | DW News
items.author: DW News
items.content:
<article>Countries dependent on trade with the US are scrambling to figure out how Donald Trump's new tariff regime will affect them. The US president announced on Saturday he was raising a new levy on imports from 10 to 15 percent.
Trump introduced that after the US Supreme Court ruled most of his previous trade tariffs were imposed illegally. Germany's Chancellor Friedrich Merz has warned that constant uncertainty about tariffs were "the biggest poison for the economies of Europe and the US." Brazil's President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva has urged Trump to treat all countries equally, saying Brazil did not want a new Cold War.

items.title: Sony, Panasonic, and the Private Capital Boom Reshaping Japan
items.author: Bloomberg Television
items.content:
<article>After decades of economic conservatism and cash hoarding, Japanese corporations are putting reform into practice. From Panasonic Automotive’s carve-out under Apollo to Sony’s pivot from electronics to entertainment, Japan’s corporate leaders are embracing a new model for long-term competitiveness.
